{"title_page": "Herb Abrams", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestling promoter and commentator}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Herb Abrams\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Herbert Charles Abrams\n| birth_date  =  {{Birth date|1955|07|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Amarillo, Texas]],<br>[[United States]]\n| death_date  =  {{Death date and age|1996|07|23|1955|07|09}} \n| death_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]],<br>[[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| spouse = Murry Abrams\n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| death_cause = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]] by [[Cocaine overdose]]\n| occupation  = Professional wrestling promoter and commentator\n| known_for   = Founder of the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]]\n}}\n\n'''Herbert Charles Abrams''' (July 9, 1955 \u2013 July 23, 1996), also known by the nickname '''Mr. Electricity,'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=2&nr=3237&gimmick=Herb+Abrams#facts|title=Herb Abrams \u00ab Wrestlers Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> was an American [[professional wrestling]] promoter from [[New York, New York|New York]] who founded the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]].\n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on Abrams and his UWF promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAbrams started out as a businessman in California, owning a chain of [[plus-size clothing]] stores for women called I'm a Big Girl Now. He also served as Committee Chair of the Builders of Jewish Education (BJE) in 1984.<ref>https://www.bjela.org/bje-history-0</ref>\n\nAbrams founded the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]] (UWF) in 1990 and remained [[CEO]] of the company until his death. In August 1990, during a press conference announcing the UWF's formation, Abrams was asked how he expected to succeed in the wrestling business despite having no prior experience in it. Abrams responded: \"What they're looking for, I have, and that's the Hollywood glitz\", completely contradicting previous statements he made about wanting to bring professional wrestling back to its roots.<ref name=mf183>Foley, Mick (1999). ''[[Have a Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks]]''. ReganBooks. {{ISBN|978-0-06-039299-4}}. p. 183</ref>\n\nHe was the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|head booker]] of the UWF from 1990 to 1992, and again in 1994. He was also a commentator for the first eleven episodes of the Universal Wrestling Federation's TV show ''Fury Hour'' alongside [[Bruno Sammartino]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=2&nr=3237&page=23|title=Commentary Career \u00ab Herb Abrams \u00ab Wrestlers Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> for which the readers of [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] voted him Worst Television Announcer of 1990. Prior to the award, Abrams had used a [[Jobber (professional wrestling)|jobber]] on television by the name of Little Davey Meltzer, a very obvious jab at the newsletter's editor and publisher [[Dave Meltzer]]. Abrams was replaced on commentary by [[Craig DeGeorge]].\n\n==Death==\nAbrams died in July 1996 in New York City. Before his death, while high on [[cocaine]], Abrams was found naked and covered in a \"vaseline\" type substance,<ref name=mf186>Foley, Mick (1999). ''[[Have a Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks]]''. ReganBooks. {{ISBN|978-0-06-039299-4}}. p. 186</ref> destroying furniture with a baseball bat<ref name=mf186/> in his New York office.<ref name=sw155/>  He was in the company of prostitutes at the time.<ref name=sw155/> Not long afterwards, he died while in police custody,<ref name=mf186/> of a heart attack.<ref name=sw155>Williams, Steve (2007). ''Steve Williams: How Dr. Death Became Dr. Life''. Sports Publishing LLC. {{ISBN|1596701803}}. p. 155</ref> He had cocaine stuck all over his body when he died.<ref name=sw155/> He was laid to rest in New York.\n\n== Awards and accomplishments ==\n*'''[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards|Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards]]'''\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (1990)\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Most Obnoxious|Most Obnoxious]] (1991)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abrams, Herb}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Cocaine-related deaths in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling executives]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n{{US-business-bio-1950s-stub}}\n{{US-prowrestling-bio-stub}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Herb Abrams\n| image       = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = Herbert Charles Abrams\n| birth_date  =  {{Birth date|1955|07|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Amarillo, Texas]],<br>[[United States]]\n| death_date  =  {{Death date and age|1996|07|23|1955|07|09}} \n| death_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]],<br>[[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n| nationality = American\n| other_names = \n| death_cause = [[Myocardial infarction|Heart attack]] by [[Cocaine overdose]]\n| occupation  = Professional wrestling promoter\n| known_for   = Founder of the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]]\n}}\n'''Herbert Charles Abrams''' (July 9, 1955 \u2013 July 23, 1996), also known by the nickname '''Mr. Electricity,'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=2&nr=3237&gimmick=Herb+Abrams#facts|title=Herb Abrams \u00ab Wrestlers Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> was an American [[professional wrestling]] promoter from [[New York, New York|New York]] who founded the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]].\n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on Abrams and his UWF promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAbrams started out as a businessman in California, owning a chain of [[plus-size clothing]] stores for women called I'm a Big Girl Now. He also served as Committee Chair of the Builders of Jewish Education (BJE) in 1984.<ref>https://www.bjela.org/bje-history-0</ref>\n\nAbrams founded the [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]] (UWF) in 1990 and remained [[CEO]] of the company until his death. In August 1990, during a press conference announcing the UWF's formation, Abrams was asked how he expected to succeed in the wrestling business despite having no prior experience in it. Abrams responded: \"What they're looking for, I have, and that's the Hollywood glitz\", completely contradicting previous statements he made about wanting to bring professional wrestling back to its roots.<ref name=mf183>Foley, Mick (1999). ''[[Have a Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks]]''. ReganBooks. {{ISBN|978-0-06-039299-4}}. p. 183</ref>\n\nHe was the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|head booker]] of the UWF from 1990 to 1992, and again in 1994. He was also a commentator for the first eleven episodes of the Universal Wrestling Federation's TV show ''Fury Hour'' alongside [[Bruno Sammartino]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=2&nr=3237&page=23|title=Commentary Career \u00ab Herb Abrams \u00ab Wrestlers Database \u00ab CAGEMATCH - The Internet Wrestling Database|website=www.cagematch.net|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref> for which the readers of [[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] voted him Worst Television Announcer of 1990. Prior to the award, Abrams had used a [[Jobber (professional wrestling)|jobber]] on television by the name of Little Davey Meltzer, a very obvious jab at the newsletter's editor and publisher [[Dave Meltzer]]. Abrams was replaced on commentary by [[Craig DeGeorge]].\n\n==Death==\nAbrams died in July 1996 in New York City. Before his death, while high on [[cocaine]], Abrams was found naked and covered in a \"vaseline\" type substance,<ref name=mf186>Foley, Mick (1999). ''[[Have a Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks]]''. ReganBooks. {{ISBN|978-0-06-039299-4}}. p. 186</ref> destroying furniture with a baseball bat<ref name=mf186/> in his New York office.<ref name=sw155/>  He was in the company of prostitutes at the time.<ref name=sw155/> Not long afterwards, he died while in police custody,<ref name=mf186/> of a heart attack.<ref name=sw155>Williams, Steve (2007). ''Steve Williams: How Dr. Death Became Dr. Life''. Sports Publishing LLC. {{ISBN|1596701803}}. p. 155</ref> He had cocaine stuck all over his body when he died.<ref name=sw155/> He was laid to rest in New York.\n\n== Awards and accomplishments ==\n\n*'''[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards|Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards]]'''\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (1990)\n**[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Most Obnoxious|Most Obnoxious]] (1991)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abrams, Herb}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:1996 deaths]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Cocaine-related deaths in 