{"title_page": "Arthur's Seat, Kandy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates |date=June 2018}}\n{{EngvarB |date=June 2018}}\n[[File:Arthur's Seat, Kandy.jpg|thumb|Arthur's Seat]]\n'''Arthur\u2019s Seat''' is a popular lookout point southwest of [[Kandy Lake]], just past the [[Wales Park|Royal Palace Park]].\n\nIt is located on Rajapihilla Mawatha at {{convert|550|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"ESR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scdp.lk/pdf/env_report/Environmental%20Screening%20Report%20for%20Arthur's%20Seat%20Viewing%20Deck,%20Rajapihilla%20Mw,%20Kandy.pdf|title=Environmental Screening Report - Arthur\u2019s Seat Viewing Deck|author=Strategic Cities Development|date=November 2014|accessdate=25 June 2018 }}</ref>  It provides a panoramic view across Kandy Lake, [[Temple of the Tooth|Sri Dalada Maligawa]], the [[Royal Palace of Kandy]] and the city centre.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nation.lk/online/2017/12/09/do-kandy-in-a-day.html|title=Do Kandy in a Day|newspaper=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)|The Nation]]|date=9 December 2017|accessdate=25 June 2018}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/znfipad/escape-storytemplate/kandy-more-than-a-sweet-tooth/news-story/a19a35e05e368526b2a35c827583c4ff|title=Kandy: More than a sweet tooth|last=Nicholson|first=Sarah|publisher=News.com.au|date=20 May 2011|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to local folklore there was a [[bungalow]] owned by a Mr. Arthur, a British tea planter, situated above the lookout, who used to view [[Kandy]] by standing on a stone seat under a tree in front of his bungalow. \n\nThe [[Kandy Municipal Council]] estimated in 2015, 1,500 tourists per day visit the location during the peak season (November to May), with 500 tourists per day in the off season.<ref name=\"SCDP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scdp.lk/pdf/social_safeguard/Kandy/Upgrading/SSR.%20Arthur%20Seat%20-Kandy.pdf|title=Social Screening Report - Arthur\u2019s Seat Viewing Deck|author=Strategic Cities Development|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=25 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2016 the Council undertook the construction of the new viewing platform at the location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crdcecbsl.lk/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Kandy-Arthurs-Seat.pdf|title=Rehabilitation of Arthur's Seat Viewing Platform at Rajapihilla Mawatha, Kandy|publisher=Central Engineering Consultancy Bureau|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> The City\u2019s Heritage Committee lodged protests against what it considered was an unsightly structure, which had resulted in the original stone seat being destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/170212/news/kandys-arthurs-seat-unseated-by-ungainly-construction-228112.html|title=Kandy\u2019s Arthur\u2019s seat unseated by ungainly construction|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]]|author=Senaratne, L. B.|date=12 February 2017|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> The new viewing platform is a {{convert|35|m|ft|abbr=on}} by {{convert|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} concrete deck with a symbolical seat made out of the original rock slab.<ref name=\"SCDP\"/> The cost of the construction was [[Sri Lankan rupee|Rs]] 6.474M,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.developmentaid.org/#!/references/view/101536/sri-lanka-strategic-cities-development-project-consultancy-services-for-construction-supervision-of|title=Strategic Cities Development Project: Consultancy Services for Construction supervision of Arthur's Seat-Kandy|publisher=Development Aid|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> funded by the [[World Bank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.worldbank.org/procurement/noticeoverview?lang=en&id=OP00047399|title=Preparation Of Detailed Engineering Design Of The Arthur's Seat, Kandy|publisher=[[World Bank]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kandy landmarks}}\n{{coord|7.2891|N|80.6400|E|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:LK-21|display=title}} <!-- source: [https://www.google.com/maps/place/Arthur's+Seat/@7.2890788,80.6400048,20z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x3ae3662f1be76e43:0xe050a6c33be5f6f7!8m2!3d7.2890788!4d80.6400048], Google Maps -->\n\n[[Category:Parks in Kandy]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Kandy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates |date=June 2018}}\n{{EngvarB |date=June 2018}}\n'''Arthur\u2019s Seat''' is a popular lookout point southwest of [[Kandy Lake]], just past the [[Wales Park|Royal Palace Park]].\n\nIt is located on Rajapihilla Mawatha at {{convert|550|m|ft|abbr=on}} above sea level.<ref name=\"ESR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scdp.lk/pdf/env_report/Environmental%20Screening%20Report%20for%20Arthur's%20Seat%20Viewing%20Deck,%20Rajapihilla%20Mw,%20Kandy.pdf|title=Environmental Screening Report - Arthur\u2019s Seat Viewing Deck|author=Strategic Cities Development|date=November 2014|accessdate=25 June 2018 }}</ref>  It provides a panoramic view across Kandy Lake, [[Temple of the Tooth|Sri Dalada Maligawa]], the [[Royal Palace of Kandy]] and the city centre.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nation.lk/online/2017/12/09/do-kandy-in-a-day.html|title=Do Kandy in a Day|newspaper=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)|The Nation]]|date=9 December 2017|accessdate=25 June 2018}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/znfipad/escape-storytemplate/kandy-more-than-a-sweet-tooth/news-story/a19a35e05e368526b2a35c827583c4ff|title=Kandy: More than a sweet tooth|last=Nicholson|first=Sarah|publisher=News.com.au|date=20 May 2011|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to local folklore there was a [[bungalow]] owned by a Mr. Arthur, a British tea planter, situated above the lookout, who used to view [[Kandy]] by standing on a stone seat under a tree in front of his bungalow. \n\nThe [[Kandy Municipal Council]] estimated in 2015, 1,500 tourists per day visit the location during the peak season (November to May), with 500 tourists per day in the off season.<ref name=\"SCDP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scdp.lk/pdf/social_safeguard/Kandy/Upgrading/SSR.%20Arthur%20Seat%20-Kandy.pdf|title=Social Screening Report - Arthur\u2019s Seat Viewing Deck|author=Strategic Cities Development|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=25 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn early 2016 the Council undertook the construction of the new viewing platform at the location.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://crdcecbsl.lk/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Kandy-Arthurs-Seat.pdf|title=Rehabilitation of Arthur's Seat Viewing Platform at Rajapihilla Mawatha, Kandy|publisher=Central Engineering Consultancy Bureau|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> The City\u2019s Heritage Committee lodged protests against what it considered was an unsightly structure, which had resulted in the original stone seat being destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/170212/news/kandys-arthurs-seat-unseated-by-ungainly-construction-228112.html|title=Kandy\u2019s Arthur\u2019s seat unseated by ungainly construction|newspaper=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)|The Sunday Times]]|author=Senaratne, L. B.|date=12 February 2017|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> The new viewing platform is a {{convert|35|m|ft|abbr=on}} by {{convert|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} concrete deck with a symbolical seat made out of the original rock slab.<ref name=\"SCDP\"/> The cost of the construction was [[Sri Lankan rupee|Rs]] 6.474M,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.developmentaid.org/#!/references/view/101536/sri-lanka-strategic-cities-development-project-consultancy-services-for-construction-supervision-of|title=Strategic Cities Development Project: Consultancy Services for Construction supervision of Arthur's Seat-Kandy|publisher=Development Aid|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> funded by the [[World Bank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.worldbank.org/procurement/noticeoverview?lang=en&id=OP00047399|title=Preparation Of Detailed Engineering Design Of The Arthur's Seat, Kandy|publisher=[[World Bank]]|date=29 November 2017|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref